Cybernetic Loop Engineering Experiment
Objective
This project explores whether improvements in autonomous software engineering come primarily from better control loops rather than better language models.
The experiment is inspired by cybernetics, where intelligent behaviour emerges through feedback, regulation and adaptation. Rather than comparing different models, we will keep the model constant and progressively add cybernetic control mechanisms around it.
The central hypothesis is:
Engineering the feedback loop surrounding an AI coding agent will improve software engineering performance more than prompt engineering alone.

⸻

Benchmark
We will use SWE-bench Verified with an initial subset of approximately 20–30 tasks.
Each task consists of:
	•	a real GitHub issue
	•	a repository snapshot
	•	a Docker evaluation environment
	•	hidden evaluation tests
Every experimental configuration will run against exactly the same benchmark subset.
The benchmark should remain fixed throughout the experiment.

⸻

Success Metrics
We intentionally keep evaluation simple.
1. Task Success Rate
Percentage of benchmark tasks successfully solved.
Primary metric.

⸻

2. Cost
Total model usage (tokens/API cost).
Measures efficiency.

⸻

3. Execution Time
Wall-clock runtime from start until completion.
Measures practical usability.

⸻

Experimental Philosophy
The model remains constant throughout the experiment.
Only the controller changes.
We are evaluating control architectures, not language models.
Each experiment introduces one additional cybernetic principle.

